      "id": 353866,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>1-Octen-3-ol, a potent mosquito attractant commonly used in mosquito traps, can be prepared in two steps from hexanal, CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CHO. The first step is an acetylide-addition reaction like that described in Problem 9-50. What is the structure of the product from the first step, and how can it be converted into 1-octen-3-ol?</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBZ01UIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--3cbdb187fec58c556e566c671ad1767572911501/OChem_09_EC_040.jpg\" alt=\"The structure of 1-octen-3-ol.\">",
